The paper deals with the study of a specific category, CNOT, which is generated by gates and computational ancillae. This makes it likely to fall under the sub-categories of Logic in Computer Science (cs.LO), Information Theory (cs.IT), Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS), Programming Languages (cs.PL), and Quantum Physics (cs.QI). The paper's focus on identities and equivalence of categories also suggests a connection to logic and information theory. The use of gates and computational ancillae suggests a connection to programming languages and data structures. Finally, the study of CNOT as a discrete inverse category and its equivalence to the category of partial isomorphisms of finitely-generated non-empty commutative torsors of characteristic 2 suggests a connection to quantum physics.
